body:
This is a poor argument for several reasons:
1. The year is only about half over, so all things held the same if COVID-19 killed half as many children as seasonal flu then it is about the equally dangerous not "LESS DANGEROUS" as the article claims.
2. All things are NOT the same. People have been self-quarantining ever since COVID-19 hit the states. So you'd expect less children to have caught the disease than they would have if schools under normal circumstances.
3. Even if COVID-19 were 100% harmless to children, if they carry it asymptomatically (which evidence shows they can), going to school means it will spread widely among the adult population of caretakers. Arguing "kids are safe" is completely missing the point.

And a fourth point: Deaths aren't the only negative outcome of COVID cases. 

There are a myriad of potential associated health issues we are still learning about (reduced lung function, blood clots, neurological issues). More hospitalizations lead to increased health care cost for everyone (similar to how obesity has an enormous economic cost). If it spreads among kids, it is virtually guaranteed to be transmitted to their parents (who we need to continue working).

I think the long-term cost of returning to business-as-usual to protect the economy will outweigh the short-term cost of keeping things closed until we have a vaccine/herd immunity.

parent.body:
This is a poor argument for several reasons:
1. The year is only about half over, so all things held the same if COVID-19 killed half as many children as seasonal flu then it is about the equally dangerous not "LESS DANGEROUS" as the article claims.
2. All things are NOT the same. People have been self-quarantining ever since COVID-19 hit the states. So you'd expect less children to have caught the disease than they would have if schools under normal circumstances.
3. Even if COVID-19 were 100% harmless to children, if they carry it asymptomatically (which evidence shows they can), going to school means it will spread widely among the adult population of caretakers. Arguing "kids are safe" is completely missing the point.
